# Apple & Android Friendly (always)

This website must look and work great on iPhone (Safari) **and** Android
(Chrome) first, then scale up to tablet and desktop. Verify every UI change
against both platforms before considering it done.

## Always do

- **Mobile-first, responsive**: design for ~375px width first; scale up with
  `sm:`/`md:`/`lg:`. Never ship a layout that overflows on a phone.
- **Touch targets ≥ 44×44px**: buttons, links, toggles, and the hamburger must
  be comfortably tappable.
- **No hover-only interactions**: anything reachable by hover must also work on
  tap/focus.
- **Respect notches/safe areas** where relevant using `env(safe-area-inset-*)`.
- **Keep PWA/install assets in sync**: `app/icon.png`, `app/apple-icon.png`,
  and `app/manifest.ts` (Android icons) must all stay valid.
- **Cross-platform rendering**: prefer assets/glyphs that render identically on
  iOS and Android. (Example: emoji country flags render as letters on some
  Android/Windows builds — use SVG flags if pixel-consistency matters.)

## Avoid

- Fixed pixel widths that break on small screens.
- Platform-only CSS without a fallback (test `backdrop-blur`, sticky headers).
- Tiny fonts/controls that fail mobile usability.

## Example

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — hover-only, tiny target
<div className="hidden hover:block">Menu</div>

// ✅ GOOD — works on tap, large enough target
<button className="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center md:hidden">
  Menu
</button>
```
